{"block": {"name": "text", "text": "<p>In 1951, David A. Huffman and his classmates in an Information Theory course were given the choice of a term paper or a final exam. The topic of the term paper: Find the most efficient method of representing numbers, letters or other symbols using a binary code. After months of working on the problem without any success, just as he was about to give up on the enticing offer of skipping an engineering course's final exam, Huffman finally solved the problem, resulting in the birth of <b>Huffman Coding</b>, an algorithm that is still widely used today.</p><p><img title=\"Image: https://ucarecdn.com/089d734e-e065-490d-919d-54d4c42d9470/\" src=\"https://ucarecdn.com/089d734e-e065-490d-919d-54d4c42d9470/\" alt=\"\"></p><p class=\"wysiwyg-text-align-center\"><b>Figure:</b>\ufeff David Huffman\u00a0expresses mathematical theorems in intricate paper sculptures (Photo: Matthew Mulbry)<br></p>", "video": null, "animation": null, "options": {}, "subtitle_files": [], "source": null, "subtitles": {}, "tests_archive": null, "feedback_correct": "", "feedback_wrong": ""}, "id": "96570", "time": "2017-09-11T11:51:13.331196"}